title: Extract a Subscriber base class from LogSubscriber
body:
I'm using the instrumentation framework heavily to do stats collection with Statsd, but have so far relied on a custom base class for attaching the various subscribers to instrument names. I'd like to use the same base class for both stats and log subscribers, hence this PR.

There should be no functional changes to how the LogSubscriber works, but now you can inherit from Subscriber if you just want the attachment logic.

What do you say?

title: AR postgres binary bug fix
body:
Currently, if a postgres table contains a record with a binary field and this record is fetched from the DB, an exception is raised if the binary data is nil.

This bug is due to the fact that the unescaping of the column value is passed directly to `PGConn` without checking for nil. `PGConn#unescape_bytea` does a check on the value type and raise an exception if the value isn't a string.

This PR adds tests around the binary type (currently no tests exist), and a fix for the mentioned bug.

fix respond_to? for non selected column
body:
fixes #4208

If a query selects only a few columns and gives custom names to
those columns then respond_to? was returning true for the non
selected columns. However calling those non selectd columns
raises exception.

    post = Post.select("'title' as post_title").first

In the above case when `post.body` is invoked then an exception is
raised since `body` attribute is not selected. Howevere `respond_to?`
did not behave correctly.

    pos.respond_to?(:body) #=> true

Reason was that Active Record calls `super` to pass the call to
Active Model and all the columns are defined on Active Model.

Fix is to actually check if the data returned from the db contains
the data for column in question.

@jonleighton can you take a look? You participated in the original issue.

title: Fix freeze applying to cloned objects
body:
Previously, freezing a cloned ActiveRecord object froze the original too. By
cloning `@attributes` before freezing, we prevent cloned objects
(which in Ruby share state of ivars) from being effected by `#freeze`.

Resolves issue #4936, which has further information on this issue, as well as
steps to reproduce.

* Add a test case for `#freeze` not causing `cloned.frozen?` to be true.
* Clone `@attributes` before freezing in `ActiveRecord::Core`, then
 reassign the cloned, frozen hash to the frozen model's `@attributes`
 ivar.

/cc @steveklabnik

title: Refactor regexp at assert_method into a constant using a string for interpolation
Adding the available_queries_for_explain thread local into the AR Runtime Registry
body:
Before, the ``:available_queries_for_explain`` thread local could be accessed by using ``Thread.current[:available_queries_for_explain]``. However, the ``ActiveRecord::RuntimeRegistry`` object has recently been added to limit the number of thread locals that are passed around.

This PR moves the handling of ``:available_queries_for_explain`` into the ``RuntimeRegistry`` object and changes the appropriate logic.
